You should all be ashamed of yourselves.


20 Sep 2010 22:37






Oh, hey, I thought we deleted the old 228. Whoops.

Guys, this is bad. I have downvoted it, and you should have downvoted it, because it's nothing but an excuse for, ahem, certain readers to, ahem, reflect on all possible ramifications of the term "anatomically correct".

The level of detail in the description is frankly unnerving. Not in the "oh, hey, spooky good shit" way, mind you, but in the "this makes yoric begin silently to wonder about the author's, ahem, inclinations, and nudge the guy next to him to get him to read it and see if he gets the same impression" sort of way. He did, too, so it's not just me.

With the necissary out of the way, I can now proceed to the chief complaint I have against this article.

This one is boring.

It's a super realistic doll, right, only it maybe used to be a realperson, see, but now it's just a doll, and you can pose it and dress it up and give it different things to hold onto, like, and change its clothes, and…

yaaaaaaaaawn.

So, yeh. My point is, there is really nothing of substance that this article brings to the site. It's a dull excuse for a certain type of person to play dressup in their heads with an ohmigod real girl who doesn't complain when their fingers brush against her ass as they "smooth her dress". It's not scary, it's not particularly interesting, it's not compelling for those of us with healthy attitudes toward females, and generally it's just not a good article.

Now, the process by which a real human was made into a sex doll (and if you claim it's not a sex doll not only are you lying through your teeth but you're missing out on a fantastic opportunity to inject some real horror into the article you pathetic sack of repressed mommy issues, you) might make an excellent SCP article. In fact, I would love to see that written. A piece detailing a medical procedure that should by all known rules of biology not work at all or simply result in the death of the victim yet here, look, these are the ones it worked on stacked in the sick bastard's closet covered in dust and suspicious stains would be fantastic. Perhaps an interview log wherein the person responsible discussed their, ahem, motive with a doctor who's trying to maintain his professionalism in the face of such a monster would be in order. That would actually frighten a few readers, and offend a few more, and interest others enough to be a worthwhile addition to the wiki. So, go do that.







